we are given a binary search tree and two nodes p and q such that p and q are part of the BST and our job is to find lowest common ancestor of the p and q;

Algorithm:
1. Start from root.

2. If both p and q are smaller than root:
   - LCA must be in the left subtree.

3. If both p and q are greater than root:
   - LCA must be in the right subtree.

4. Otherwise:
   - One node is on the left and one node is on the right.
   - Or one node is equal to root.
   - So current root is the LCA.


Code:
class Solution {
    public TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {

        int parentVal = root.val;
        int pVal = p.val;
        int qVal = q.val;

        // Both nodes are greater, so LCA is in right subtree
        if (pVal > parentVal && qVal > parentVal) {
            return lowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p, q);
        }

        // Both nodes are smaller, so LCA is in left subtree
        if (pVal < parentVal && qVal < parentVal) {
            return lowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p, q);
        }

        // Nodes split on both sides, so current root is LCA
        return root;
    }
}
